Introduction¶

This report will analyze FBI gun data from the National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS). This system is used by gun sellers (for example, gun stores, pawn shops, etc.) to determine if the buyer is legally permitted to make the purchase. More information about the program can be found on the FBI's NICS page.

Specifically, the NICS dataset used in this analysis is an .xlsx file that contains the number of background checks per month by state and by type of check (for example, permit, handgun, long gun, etc.) from November 1998 to September 2017. The source of the data is from Buzz Feed News, who aggregated data obtained from the FBI. They mention that the original data from the FBI included the following very important caveat regarding what the data can tell us:

These statistics represent the number of firearm background checks initiated through the NICS. They do not represent the number of firearms sold. Based on varying state laws and purchase scenarios, a one-to-one correlation cannot be made between a firearm background check and a firearm sale.

For the purpose of this report, I think it is safe to assume that the background checks can be used as an indicator of interest in purchasing a firearm.

This data is supplemented with U.S. Census data provided by the Udacity Data Analyst Nanodegree program. The linked .csv file contains statistics per state regarding population, education levels, per capita income, poverty levels, etc.

In this analysis we will investigate the following questions.

(1) Is interest in gun purchases cyclical? For example, can we determine if there is more interest after specific events, such as presidential elections? Are there any patterns that we can see over time?

(2) People from which states show the most intetest in obtaining a firearm? (i.e. which states have the most background checks per capita?)

(3) Which demographic characteristics are most correlated with an interest in purchasing a firearm? Specifically, are education levels, poverty rates, and population density (i.e. more or less urban or rural) correlated with the number of background checks?

Most of the column names refer to a very specific type of check, for example handgun rental, pawn redemption for a long gun, etc. More detail about what these columns specifically refer to can be found at on the first page of the FBI's most recent set of data. (Note we are actually using an older dataset, however the column names still correspond to our data.) Given the nature of our questions, we won't need all of this detail, so we can probably drop several of these later. Also, all of the column names are lowercase and none have spaces, so we don't need to modify them.

Most of the columns are 64 bit floating point numbers. The date and month are stored as text and admin and totals are 64 bit integers. We could potentially convert the floating point types to integer, as we should not be dealing with fractionally values of a background check, provided we decide to keep these columns. We could convert the month field to a date format, however for our analysis there is no harm in leaving it in text format. The remaining columns have the correct data type.

Additionally, we can also see that most of the columns contain some null values. Only four columns don't contain nulls: month, state, admin, and totals.

We'll need to investigate the nulls further, but first let's check to see if any of the rows are duplicates.

We have just confirmed that there are nulls in the data starting from July 2016 and going back in time. Scrolling through the .xlsx file, it appears that certain columns were added for tracking over time. In the example above, it looks like rentals of both handguns and long guns were added from August 2016 onward.

So, how do we handle these nulls? There are a few options: For example, we could fill them with zeros or we could fill them with the mean value for that particular column. Additionally, we could drop the rows or the columns containing nulls.

First, given that there are only 770 rows that don't contain nulls (out of dataset containing 12485 rows), dropping rows with nulls doesn't sound like the best option. We could, however, consider dropping some of the columns, especially if they don't pertain to any of the questions that we will be analyzing.

In order to determine the best course of action, let's see how the 'totals' column is being tracked. This column represents the total of all backgound checks in a given months. Is it a sum of all of the columns from 'permit' to 'return_to_seller_other', meaning that the categories represented by the columns are mutually exclusive? Or, is it possible that a background check can be counted as both 'permit' and 'handgun', meaning that the categories aren't mutually exclusive?

In [8]:
# Sum the categories by row (from "permit" to "return_to_seller_other")
sum_of_cats_by_row = df_guns.loc[:,"permit":"return_to_seller_other"].sum(axis=1)
# See if there are any rows were the sum of all of the categories is not equal to the value in "totals"
df_guns[df_guns.totals != sum_of_cats_by_row]
Out[8]:
month state permit permit_recheck handgun long_gun other multiple admin prepawn_handgun ... returned_other rentals_handgun rentals_long_gun private_sale_handgun private_sale_long_gun private_sale_other return_to_seller_handgun return_to_seller_long_gun return_to_seller_other totals

0 rows 27 columns

As we can see from the above, the sum of each of the categories is equal to the value in the totals column (otherwise the second statement would have returned values), therefore the categories are mutally exclusive and we can fill our nulls with zeros. This is a better solution than filling them with the average value of the column, as we would lose the property of mutually exclusivity. However, we need to keep in mind that just because we have filled in zeros in a particular column that doesn't mean that it accurately reflects the absense of that type of transaction. For example, a background check classified as handgun could have possibly been classified in another category, such as pre-pawn handgun, at a later date when that category was added.

Additionally, we should note that zeros for a given category could indicate that a state does not require background checks for that type of transaction, not that one didn't occur for that given month. For example, not every state requires background checks for private sales. This should be kept in mind when making comparisons between states. Please consult the FBI NICS link above for more information.

Next, we will address the issue of potentially errant data. One big source of errant data is when data does not have the correct data type, such when numeric values are being stored as text. We don't have that issue in this dataset. However, we should check that our columns that are of floating point type don't have any fractional values, as the number of background checks should be whole numbers. We can do a quick test this using modular arithmetic on each of the floating point columns.

NICS Data Cleaning¶

Our analysis above identified four issues to fix:

(1) Replace our null values with zeros.\ (2) Change floating point columns to integers.\ (3) Remove territories and the District of Columbia.\ (3) Remove columns that won't be used from our dataframe.

First, let's remove the territories and District of Columbia.

It looks like the 'Fact' column indicates what type of census statistic is represented in the row. The 'Fact Note' column contains any futher explanation of the former. The remaining columns list each state. There are spaces in between some of the column names that we may need to address later.

One thing that stands out is that it might be easier to actually invert the table, transforming the type of census information in 'Fact' into columns. Then each row could reference a state. We could shorten each of the current facts into lowercase column names without spaces. We can leave the text fields of the state alone and verify later that we can join them with the states in our background check data.

There also appear to be some errant or inconsistent values. For example, in the 'Population, percent change...' row, most of the values are listed as a percentage, but some states like South Dakota and Tennessee have decimal values. We will need to fix this so that all of our values are converted into decimal values.

Let's look at how many of these 'Facts' we currently have and see if we if we need all of them.

Census Data Cleaning¶

Our analysis above identified a number issues that will need to be addressed before using the census data:

(1) Invert our dataframe\ (2) Drop unnecessary Facts\ (3) Rename Facts (elimate spaces and use lowercase)\ (4) Convert numbers to float or integer, depending on what they represent, removing any % signs or commas in the process\ (5) Address data inconsistencies. For example, some states have decimal values instead of percentages for certain census 'Facts'

Let's start by dropping the 'Facts' that we don't need. The questions that we are investigating involve population, education level (high school and university graduation rates), per capita income, poverty rate, and population density. These are represented by indexes 0, 34, 35, 48, 49 and 62 respectively. Let's keep these and drop the rest. Let's also drop the 'Fact Note' column.

Earlier we mentioned that some of the fields that contained percentages were inconsistent. The three remaining percentage columns are 'high_school', 'university' and 'poverty'. In [31]:

# Some values in these 3 columns were already in decimal form (New Mexico through Tennesee).

for row in df_census.index: 
    if (df_census.iloc[row].state not in ['New Mexico', 'New York', 'North Carolina', 'North Dakota', 'Ohio', 'Oklahoma', 'Oregon', 'Pennsylvania', 'Rhode Island', 'South Carolina', 'South Dakota', 'Tennessee']):
        df_census.at[row, 'high_school'] /= 100
        df_census.at[row, 'university'] /= 100
        df_census.at[row, 'poverty'] /= 100

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Research Question 1: Patterns in background checks over time¶

Is interest in gun purchases cyclical? For example, can we determine if there is more interest after specific events, such as presidential elections? Are there any patterns that we can see over time?

In order to examine how the number of background checks evolve over time, we first need to get the sum of all of our columns by month.

Next, let's create a line graph of our total number of background checks per month in order to see if there's any sort of pattern.

In [40]:
# Set the figure size to be large since we have a lot of time values
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"]=(50, 50)

# Line graph plotting function
def plot_line_graph(xvals, yvals, title ,xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.plot(xvals, yvals)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    # space out ticks
    # source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54783160/x-axis-tick-labels-are-too-dense-when-drawing-plots-with-matplotlib
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.set_xticks(ax.get_xticks()[::3])
    plt.show();

# Configure parameters and call the function
title = 'Gun Background Checks over Time'
xlabel = 'Month'
ylabel = 'Total Background Checks in Millions'
xvals = sum_by_months.index
yvals = sum_by_months.totals
plot_line_graph(xvals, yvals, title ,xlabel, ylabel)

There are some interesting observations that we can make. First, there does appear to be a trend. I had intially wondered whether interest in firearms purchases could be related to certain events, i.e. who won a presidential election or concern over new restrictions being imposed due to mass shootings, etc.

However, looking at the plot, we can see that yearly peaks for background checks are regular and highest point seems occur around December of each year. Up until about 2010, there is a fairly regular pattern: The December peak is followed by a sharp drop and then a second smaller peak around March. After that the number of checks descends until about July, after which is increases to reach a high in December again. Starting around 2010 we still seek peaks around December and valleys in the summer, although the pattern is a little less regular.

This December peak could possibly indicate that guns are being purchased around the holidays, hence the higher number of background checks. An item that can be explored further is whether or not the background checks in December correspond to a particular type (handgun, long gun, permit) and/or are different from the types of background checks that occur at other times during the year.

Second, we can see that the number of background checks overall does appear to be increasing in general over time. Our peaks get increasingly higher and the valleys in later years aren't as low as they are in the earlier years. A point for futher exploration might be to determine how much of this increase is related to the overall increase in population in the United States during these years. Also, we might explore whether the increase in background checks is due to an increase in regulations as more states require background checks on firearm sales in more types of transactions (i.e. private sales, required permits, etc.) These last two questions are out of scope for the data that we're analyzing for this project, however we can dig deeper and explore how the three different types of background checks mentioned above (handgun, long gun, permit) compare over time.

Before we move on, because our graph is small and might be hard to read, let's print out lists of both the peaks and valleys of each complete calendar year so that we can verify that the conclusions above about peaks and valleys are correct.

Research Question 2: Background Checks per capital per state¶

People from which states show the most intetest in obtaining a firearm (i.e. which states have the most background checks per capita)? Which states show the least interest?

First, just to get a general feel for our data let's look at the total number of background checks for each state.

Note that our total checks aren't normalized by the state's population, i.e. a state might have a large number of background checks vs. another state, but because they have a different population sizes, it is difficult to assess whether one state shows more interest in gun purchases than another. Let's fix that.

We'll need to create a new dataframe that merges total background checks by state with the census data by state. First, we'll create a dataframe with states and totals.

Research Question 3: Correlation of census characteristics¶

Which demographic characteristics are most correlated with an interest in purchasing a firearm as measured by number of background checks? Specifically, are education levels, poverty rates, and population density (i.e. more or less urban or rural) correlated?

First, let's take a look at how the checks per capita correlates to a state's poverty rate.

    plt.ylabel(ylabel);

We can see that as the poverty rate increases, the number of background checks doesn't seem to vary much, therefore we can conclude that the two don't seem to be correlated.

Conclusions¶

In this report we investigated interest in guns by state using the number of background checks as the key, albeit rough, indicator. First, we plotted the total number of background checks by year and saw that there appears to be a cyclical pattern. Interest, as measured by the number of background checks, peaks around December of a given year, while it falls to a low during the summer months. Also, the number of background checks has been steadily increasing over the years. We must be carefull and not necessarily jump to the conclusion that this indicates that interest in guns keeps increasing over time, as there could be other factors that are causing the number of background checks to increase, such as increasing regulations requiring checks, as well as general population growth.

Next, we turned our attention to determining which states appear to show the most and least interest in guns based upon the total number of background checks per capita. We determined that Kentucky, Montana and West Virginia had the highest number of checks per capita, while New Jersey, Hawaii and New York had the fewest number of checks per capita. Again, we must be careful in assuming that this result is an absolute indicator of interest, as not all states require certain types of background checks. For example, some states do not require background checks for private sales.

Finally, we looked at whether or not certain census statistics are correlated to the number of background checks. While poverty rate and high school education level didn't show correlation, university education and population density do appear to be slightly negatively correlated. We double-checked university and population density rates for our top and bottom states against the respective mean and median values and they generally do appear to fit the pattern.
